      "acceptanceCriteria": "Material properties traceable to lot-specific coupon testing; geometry from calibrated CMM measurements of production hardware.",
      "rationale": "Geometry derived from coordinate measuring machine data (±5 µm accuracy) on production screws. Material properties sourced from lot-specific tensile coupon tests (n=5 per lot). Input uncertainty propagated via ±1 SD sensitivity analysis; QoI sensitivity to input variation within 3%."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "N≥10 constructs from production lots; sample dimensions verified post-test.",
      "rationale": "N=11 constructs assembled from three production lots tested across two independent laboratories. Post-test dimensional inspection confirmed no anomalous deformation prior to fracture. Sample representativeness is adequate."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Testing conducted under at least two distinct loading configurations or environmental conditions to bound the model's operational envelope; inter-laboratory variability quantified.",
      "rationale": "All experimental constructs were tested under a single ASTM F1717 standardized loading configuration (35 mm offset, room temperature, displacement-controlled at 5 mm/min). Inter-laboratory reproducibility was confirmed and coefficient of variation across labs was below 5%, demonstrating good experimental consistency. The standardized protocol is the accepted regulatory benchmark for this device class, and results fell within pre-specified acceptance bounds for all three QoIs."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "FEA boundary conditions and loading replicate experimental fixture geometry and displacement rate to within measurement uncertainty.",
      "rationale": "Fixture geometry, offset distance (35.0 mm ± 0.2 mm), and applied displacement profile were matched between FEA and experiment. Displacement rate effects assessed as negligible for quasi-static regime. Input parameter equivalency is confirmed."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison using E/uval metric (acceptance: E/uval < 1.96) and percentage difference < 10% for all three QoIs.",
      "rationale": "E/uval values: stiffness 0.83, yield force 1.21, force at 40 mm 1.04. Percentage differences: stiffness 3.2%, yield force 6.8%, force at 40 mm 4.1%. All metrics within pre-specified acceptance bounds. Output comparison is satisfactory."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm) directly map to clinical performance indicators and regulatory submission requirements.",
      "rationale": "The three QoIs are explicitly required by FDA guidance for spinal fixation systems under ASTM F1717. Stiffness governs load transfer to the fusion mass; yield force and force at 40 mm bound fatigue and fracture risk. QoI relevance is high."
